{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17521483","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17521483"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:34:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:34:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13684"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13684","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13684"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.07,0.72,0.03,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6292"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90831"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6292","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6292"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13684"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74894"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"2234"},{"type":"tags","id":"2701"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11648"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13368"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14781"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14918"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31094"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31130"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43429"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44396"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90831","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90831"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 54-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a seven-day history of fever, productive cough, and left-sided pleuritic chest pain. She has a past medical history of rheumatoid arthritis, and is currently on methotrexate and prednisone. She does not take any other regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell with a pulse rate of 118/min, a blood pressure of 96/60 mmHg, respiratory rate of 28/min, SpO2 92% on room air, and temperature of 39.5\u00b0C. Chest examination reveals decreased air entry, increased vocal fremitus, and dullness to percussion at the left lung base. A chest X-ray shows a moderate left-sided pleural effusion with air-fluid levels.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pulmonary embolism with secondary pulmonary infarction","Pleural tuberculosis","Empyema","Diaphragm perforation","Uncomplicated pneumonia"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation and chest X-ray findings are most consistent with a diagnosis of \u003Cstrong\u003Eempyema\u003C/strong\u003E. An empyema is a collection of pus within the pleural space, usually due to a bacterial infection. Risk factors include pneumonia, thoracic surgery, trauma, and immunocompromised states such as diabetes mellitus and immunosuppressive medications like methotrexate and prednisone, as seen in this patient with rheumatoid arthritis. Patients typically present with fever, productive cough, and pleuritic chest pain. Physical examination may reveal decreased breath sounds, increased vocal fremitus, and dullness to percussion over the affected area. Chest X-ray shows a pleural effusion, often with loculations or air-fluid levels indicating gas-forming organisms. Definitive diagnosis requires sampling of the pleural fluid, which will show pus or a positive Gram stain or culture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUncomplicated pneumonia\u003C/strong\u003E can cause pleural effusion, but the presence of air-fluid levels in the pleural space indicates that the infection has progressed to empyema. A simple parapneumonic effusion from pneumonia would appear as a homogeneous opacity on chest X-ray without loculations or air-fluid levels. Empyema requires drainage of the infected fluid, in addition to antibiotic therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulmonary embolism with secondary pulmonary infarction\u003C/strong\u003E can cause pleuritic chest pain and pleural effusion, but would not typically cause fever, productive cough, or purulent fluid with air-fluid levels in the pleural space. While pulmonary infarction can lead to necrosis and occasionally cavitation, the patient\u0027s presentation with fever and productive cough in the context of immunosuppression makes empyema more likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPleural tuberculosis\u003C/strong\u003E can present with fever, cough, and pleural effusion, but typically has a more indolent course than the acute presentation described with other constitutional symptoms such as weight loss described. While tuberculosis can cause loculated effusions, air-fluid levels are uncommon unless there is a bronchopleural fistula. On cytology, tuberculous effusions are usually lymphocyte-predominant rather than purulent, which can assist in differentiating from empyema.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiaphragm perforation\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with acute abdominal pain and respiratory distress. While it can lead to air-fluid levels in the pleural space due to abdominal contents entering the thoracic cavity, it would not typically present with a seven-day history of fever and productive cough. Diaphragm perforation is usually associated with trauma, recent surgery, or severe vomiting (Boerhaave syndrome), none of which are mentioned in this patient\u0027s history.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Empyema typically presents with fever, productive cough, and pleuritic chest pain.","Physical examination of empyema patients may reveal decreased breath sounds, increased vocal fremitus, and dullness to percussion.","Empyema is characterised by purulent fluid in the pleural space, often with air-fluid levels on imaging."],"references":["Garvia V, Paul M. Empyema. In: StatPearls [Online]. 2024 [cited 2024 Jun 30]. Available at: http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK459237/","Weerakkody Y. Pleural empyema | Radiology Reference Article. In: Radiopaedia. 2024 [cited 2024 Jun 30]. Available at: https://radiopaedia.org/articles/pleural-empyema-1","Heffner JE, Klein JS, Hampson C. Diagnostic Utility and Clinical Application of Imaging for Pleural Space Infections. CHEST. 2010;137(2):467-79. Available at: https://journal.chestnet.org/article/S0012-3692(10)60096-7/fulltext"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74894"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13684"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74894","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74894"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-14T16:40:14+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-18T08:35:15+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6292"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90831"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Disease